label.value: curing or aging 12 months or over

definition.value: LanguaL curation note: Used when lactose is removed from the food product as when washing curd for cheese preparation. When lactose content is reduced by enzymatic conversion of lactose, use *LACTOSE CONVERTED*.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a clotting enzyme is added to a food product at any level.

LanguaL curation note: Used for products in which two or more phases are mixed very finely but not at the molecular level. A very fine dispersion of a solid in a liquid is called a suspension. A very fine dispersion of one liquid in another immiscible liquid is called an emulsion.

label.value: partial fat removal process, 50% or more remaining

definition.value: LanguaL curation note: Used for food products that have had fat partially removed to leave more than 50% fat from a full fat product. An example would 2% milk where full fat milk is 4%.

label.value: partial fat removal process, less than 50% remaining

definition.value: LanguaL curation note: Used for food products that have had fat removed to leave less than 50% fat from a full fat product. Examples would be 1% milk or 1/2% milk, where full fat milk is 4%.
LanguaL curation note: Used when an animal fat or oil is sprayed on the product or when an animal fat or oil is among the first three ingredients in order of predominance in a breading or coating.
Modified through a physical or chemical procedure by forcing a food mixture through a die to achieve a particular shape.
LanguaL curation note: Includes chocolate coatings for such products as candy and ice cream products as well as icings and frostings for such products as cakes and doughnuts.
LanguaL curation note: Used for foods that have a coating or icing made from carob.
LanguaL curation note: Used when foods or liquids (or a combination) are aerated by vigorously mixing them using a whip, whisk, spoon, spatula, rotary beater or electric mixer.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a solid fat (butter, margarine, shortening) is aerated to a creamy appearance, often with the addition of sugar.
LanguaL curation note: Used when caramelized sugar is the second or third ingredient in order of predominance or if the caramelized sugar content is known to be 5% or more.
A convenience class for food indexers that encompases dried or candied fruit products.
LanguaL curation note: Used for any process such as rolling or pounding that is applied to dough, paste or meat (veal, chicken breast) in order to flatten the appearance.
A stabilizer is a food additive that thickens, prevents separation, prevents flavor deterioration, retards oxidation by increasing the viscosity or gives a smooth texture to the food.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a food additive, such as msg or a stabilizer, is added at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a cellulose derivative (e.g., carboxymethyl cellulose, microcrystalline cellulose, etc.) is added to a food at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when carboxymethyl cellulose is added at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a gum is added as a stabilizer to a food at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a seed gum (e.g., carob bean gum, guar gum, etc.) is added to a food at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a plant exudate gum (e.g., karaya gum, gum arabic) is added to a food at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when seaweed extract (e.g., carrageenan, agar, etc.) is added to a food at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a microbial gum (e.g., xanthan gum, dextran, etc.) is added to a food at any level.
LanguaL curation note: Used primarily for processing of seeds, such as coffee, spices, nuts, and cacao beans.
LanguaL curation note: Used when a juice, typically orange, has undergone a process specified in 21 CFR 146.148 to reduce the adicity of the food.

LanguaL curation note: Used when a food such as meat, fish or vegetables are soaked in a seasoned liquid in order to absorb flavor and, in some instances, to be tenderized. Most marinades contain an acid (lemon juice, vinegar, wine) and herbs or spices; the acid ingredient serves as the tenderizer.
LanguaL curation note: Used for food products (typically fruit, cheese or meat) that have had the rind removed.
LanguaL curation note: If wheat sourdough was added use also *WHEAT ADDED [H0319]*. If rye sourdough was added use also *RYE ADDED [H0337]*.

Wheat malt is malted grain made of wheat. Malt is germinated cereal grain that has been dried in a process known as "malting". The grain is made to germinate by soaking in water and is then halted from germinating further by drying with hot air.

Rendering is a process that converts waste animal tissue into stable, value-added materials. Rendering can refer to any processing of animal byproducts into more useful materials, or more narrowly to the rendering of whole animal fatty tissue into purified fats like lard or tallow. Rendering can be carried out on an industrial, farm, or kitchen scale.
A claim that magnesium has been added to an edible product.
